<font size="4"><b>Chapter IX: Pacific Scuttlebutts</b></font>
[p. <i>62</i>] | [<a href="psyc.get.jpg.aspx?display=page&amp;legacyid=1000048379-I00060&amp;api=new&amp;maxwidth=700">Page Image</a>]<br />

When boarding the <i>West Point</i> we were impressed by the
language of the sailors; in the course of our trip we began using
some of their terms. Our corpsmen began to speak of "mess"
instead of "chow." The floor of our cabins became "the deck."
The term "scuttlebutt" intrigued us, and later on New Guinea
the numerous rumors were always referred to as "scuttlebutts."
It was difficult to ascertain which were true; the surprising aspect
was that most reports later proved so.


Our hospital unit was stirred from lethargy on May 1st by
the rumor that we were alerted for transfer to a combat zone.
We discussed the news over our morning coffee. To state that
we ruminated with avidity is no exaggeration. The 37th Field
Hospital was assigned to the Sixth Army, commanded by General
Alvin Krueger. Officers of the Sixth Army inspected our
hospital. They informed us that we would be assigned to a
task force, and the staging was planned at Finschhafen.


The next month, it appeared, would be the most interesting
period of our army careers. We would finally utilize all the
training of the preceding two years. The medical corpsmen
had been trained and retrained, using simply a lecture system.
They were anxious to begin practical work. We felt that we
were needed in the forward area; we were restless to move up.


That night I lay awake for a long period entertaining random
thoughts about this World War and about the immediate future.
The southern skies were more beautiful than ever before
on this clear night. The stars and nebulae of the Milky Way
were brighter than usual; the Milky Way appeared as if someone

[p. <i>63</i>] | [<a href="psyc.get.jpg.aspx?display=page&amp;legacyid=1000048379-I00061&amp;api=new&amp;maxwidth=700">Page Image</a>]<br />

Another piece of news intrigued us and caused us to speculate
that we might soon begin the great offensives which would bring
peace to the Far East. Persistent rumors in May, 1944 were
that our armies would be in the Philippines at Christmas. It
did not seem possible. We regarded the Philippines as impregnable
to a sea attack before Japanese bases were softened by
bombings from China. Future campaigns involving the Celebes,
Java, Sumatra and other sector of the Malay Archipelago
seemed necessary to cut Japan off from supplies of tin and
rubber. And it appeared that we must have bases in this area
in order to get a foothold in China reasonably closes to the
Philippine Islands.


We were soon to leave the Milne Bay area, so a trip into
the China Straits to the small island Samarai was planned. We
took off early in the morning of May 10th on a launch and
an L.C.M. boat to visit the mission at Samarai; we were told
it was an interesting experiment in education of the natives.
It took almost four hours to arrive at our destination. Finally
we found the mission; it is about two miles from the village
called Samarai. This village is planted high on a mountainous
island overlooking a cove. We immediately had our lunch, consisting

[p. <i>64</i>] | [<a href="psyc.get.jpg.aspx?display=page&amp;legacyid=1000048379-I00062&amp;api=new&amp;maxwidth=700">Page Image</a>]<br />

Mr. Abel was a tall, sensitive Australian, about forty years
old. The mission had been established by his parents in 1890
and he was born there. At that date this area was populated by
headhunters. The island was described well in the book <i>Headhunting
in the Solomons</i>. The elder Abels taught the barbaric
women to sew and weave and the men were instructed in carpentry.
Christianity was introduced, and in 1924 construction
of the church was begun. It was not completed in 1944. The
architecture of the church was excellent and evidenced painful,
fine construction work. The finer decorative woods in the interior
required fourteen years in preparation and carving.


The home of the Abels had remained fifty-four years with
little change; it was the most comfortable and inviting spot we
had seen for several months. The house was built around a central
roofed patio and had a spacious glass enclosed porch.
There were many overstuffed and wicker chairs littered about
on the veranda; woven mats were distributed at random. On
the side tables were small statuettes, handiwork of the natives.
Planted along this spacious porch were varicolored hanging
hibiscus; and these lent much to the beauty of this spot in the
tropics.


The natives, apparently because of two generations of kindness
and teaching, seemed far more responsive than any we
had previously seen in New Guinea. They were well clothed
and clean; their children seemed happy. They did not have
the filthy black discoloration of their teeth as they didn't chew
betel leaves or betel nuts. They were reasonably industrious;
some worked on a plantation, others worked in a sawmill or
did weaving and carving.


Mr. and Mrs. Abel were quietly hospitable and entertained
us in their library. This soft, comfortable lounge contained
many fine, well-worn volumes; this room seemed almost articulate
in inviting you to pick a book and ease into pleasant
reading. These people were giving a good share of their lives

