Some War Paint Streaked
On His Brow!</div>
[p. <i>[NA]</i>] | [<a href="psyc.get.jpg.aspx?display=page&amp;legacyid=1000048379-I00070&amp;api=new&amp;maxwidth=700">Page Image</a>]<br />
<img src="psyc.get.jpg.aspx?api=new&amp;legacyid=1000048379-I013&amp;maxwidth=640" /><br />
<a href="javascript: __showhidenote('_caption_9019');">caption</a><div id="_caption_9019" style="display:none;background-color:#FFDD99;margin:0px;border:1px solid #800000; padding:2px;">Typical New Guinea
Children</div>
<img src="psyc.get.jpg.aspx?api=new&amp;legacyid=1000048379-I014&amp;maxwidth=640" /><br />
<a href="javascript: __showhidenote('_caption_9138');">caption</a><div id="_caption_9138" style="display:none;background-color:#FFDD99;margin:0px;border:1px solid #800000; padding:2px;">Jap Captives</div>
[p. <i>65</i>] | [<a href="psyc.get.jpg.aspx?display=page&amp;legacyid=1000048379-I00071&amp;api=new&amp;maxwidth=700">Page Image</a>]<br />

We returned at dusk, trolling through the China Straits with
our deep-sea fishing equipment. We had been impressed by
this oasis of civilization in the wilds of New Guinea. Generations
hence only the church and markers would be evidence
of the work of these few white missionaries. In the year 2144
a few blacks in the area would know how to weave and could
raise better yams. They might be clothed better and would be
freer of disease. These changes, in part, would be the fruits of
this labor.


Formal retreat, a prayer by our chaplain, ice cream and a
huge cake, with a single candle, were the order of the day on
May 25. The 37th Field Hospital was celebrating its first birthday.
It had cut its teeth near the Spoon River in Illinois and
now was an equipped, fairly experienced unit, eager to begin
functional employment. Our nurses, who were on detached
service at the 124th Station Hospital, were invited to join us
for dinner. We "broke out" clean khakis and shined our heavy
field shoes. Afterward we crashed the gate at the base officers'
club. We had our first Cokes since leaving the <i>West Point</i>.


The officers' club was only a rod from the ocean beach. The
whitecaps were silvery in the moonlight. We stood at the rail
and listened to the gentle lapping of the waves; there was a
cool, steady breeze coming off the ocean. Lights of ships at sea
dotted the horizon; they were headed into the protected shores
of Milne Bay.


The nurses had changed in these several months and seemed
more satisfied with their lot. They had found ways to make
themselves look presentable despite the drabness of their issue
clothes. They had cut their leggings short and had found some
white or light tan slacks to use for dress clothes. Brown or white
safari jackets were imported from Australia; these added much
to their appearance. The yellow, atabrine-tinged color of their

[p. <i>66</i>] | [<a href="psyc.get.jpg.aspx?display=page&amp;legacyid=1000048379-I00072&amp;api=new&amp;maxwidth=700">Page Image</a>]<br />

The nurses made a better adjustment to this tropical life
than did our enlisted men. There were several reasons; they
had some diversion and professional work when on detached
service with station hospitals. Their living quarters and rations
in the hospitals were far better than those of the corpsmen.
These reasons, in part, explain why the soldiers were so discontented
during the early months in New Guinea. The best
barometer of morale among the men was their mail. The medical
officers censored it, and we found the letters a constant
source of entertainment. I made copies of many representative
letters; they vary from the following brief note to longer letters
of discontent and longing. All serve to picture the Midwestern
and Southern soldier somewhat confused and bewildered by war.


Dear Bessie:


Please send me the Kokomo Tribune.


Pvt. C.


Thanks Don and Bessie.


Somewhere in New Guinea


Dear Charley:


Just received a letter from Don and Bessie. They sent
me your letter and from the sound of it I'll be seeing you
soon. We have been out here for about three months and
it gets better every day. I don't understand how you young

[p. <i>67</i>] | [<a href="psyc.get.jpg.aspx?display=page&amp;legacyid=1000048379-I00073&amp;api=new&amp;maxwidth=700">Page Image</a>]<br />

Yours.


Hello Mom:


Will answer your letter received yesterday. I also had
a letter from Ruby and Carl the same day. Carl said he
was getting a furlough in seven more months. I sure will
be glad when he gets it. Because it realy makes a Souldier
feel good to leave camp once in a while. Mom I have sent
you eighty dollars. I sent it the first of May. You will receive
it before long. I will send you more later. Mom the
next time you see Margie S. tell her to send me one of her
nice pictures. there's a guy which is my Friend would like
to see her picture. I would like to see her myself. Mom if
you could send me an Ink-Pen Please do it. Your son.


Dear Mamey: Will write you. As I am adding more to
my writting list. I have a boy friend which is sleeping in
the same tent as I am slepping in his name is———. He
said you were his third cousin and you weren't bad looking
at all. Sure love to write all the girls. I love to write
letters and receive them also. Your cousin and I have been
together about ten months. We sure have lots of fun together.
We are in a nice coca-nut grove. Which could be
in New Guinea. This is a wonderful place down here...
and I goes swimming in the salt water about every day. it
sure is fun to swim. We have lots of bananas, Pine apples
and Coca nuts in New Guinea. Well I'll be closing for
now. Hope to hear from you soon. Just a friend.



[p. <i>68</i>] | [<a href="psyc.get.jpg.aspx?display=page&amp;legacyid=1000048379-I00074&amp;api=new&amp;maxwidth=700">Page Image</a>]<br />

Dear Joe:


Wrote you a long air mail letter last night. So will just
drop you a little line today. I have to go work today and
I'm going to try to catch a nap first. I slept till noon today
then played volley ball all afternoon. Some of the "Timber
twigs" went fishing today and brought home 10 nice fish
about like we use to catch. We have the coffee on now and
after while we are going to fry the fish. It will be the first
good meal I've had in a long time. That G-I food is good
stuf but the mess seargent makes slop out of it. Well Honey
must close the coffee is done and I want to help fry the
fish. We sure have a nice fire going in front of the tent.
Its sure a nice night out. Not raining for a change. Good
night. Lots of Love.


Two more letters deserve quotation. The first is only a portion
of a message home; the second is characteristic of the almost
primitive yearning which developed in some of the enlisted men:
<blockquote>
<p align="right">
New Guinea<br />
<i>May 10</i>, 1944
</p>
<p>
... Well Honey must close. I'm going out in front of the
tent and shoot the bull with all the other "Timber Twigs."
We talk about everything from our wife and kids up to
F. D. R. and Elinore. By the way you know how to vote.
Not the way I did the last three times. Don't tell all my
democrat friends I said that. I might want to run for "Latrine"
orderly some day....
</p>
<p align="right">
"New Guinea"
</p>
<p>
Dearest Precious Wife:
</p>
<p>
My love I love you forever and ever. I am so awfully
lonesome for you darling. My honey I had my bandage
change out in the air. It doesn't look like rain even it if
does sweetheart I am right here I can hobble around. My
