lovely wife you are every thing I live for. Queenie love are
you receiving two letters a day? Honey please take care of
yourself dear. Lovely beauty did you send me a colored
picture of you yet? Honey do me one favor. Get a colored
picture of yourself every month honey and send it to me
dearest. Lovely wife no mail for today yet. I am kissing
our ring. Can you feel it sweetheart? Honey tell me how
much you love me. Queenie love don't worry my foot is
allright. Honey I love you. I need you dearest so much.
Darling love your so cute and pretty. Hugs Loves and
Kisses. Your devoted Husband.
</blockquote>

New Guinea<br />
<i>May 10</i>, 1944


... Well Honey must close. I'm going out in front of the
tent and shoot the bull with all the other "Timber Twigs."
We talk about everything from our wife and kids up to
F. D. R. and Elinore. By the way you know how to vote.
Not the way I did the last three times. Don't tell all my
democrat friends I said that. I might want to run for "Latrine"
orderly some day....


"New Guinea"


Dearest Precious Wife:


My love I love you forever and ever. I am so awfully
lonesome for you darling. My honey I had my bandage
change out in the air. It doesn't look like rain even it if
does sweetheart I am right here I can hobble around. My

[p. <i>69</i>] | [<a href="psyc.get.jpg.aspx?display=page&amp;legacyid=1000048379-I00075&amp;api=new&amp;maxwidth=700">Page Image</a>]<br />

The above writer was daily brimming over with affection;
unfortunately his vocabulary was limited. His two daily letters
conformed to this type. Finally we'd take a look at the salutation,
and the letter was passed. We came to a unanimous
conclusion that there were no military secrets contained and
that his "Queenie" should not doubt his love!


We waited expectantly for further news during the month
of May. Our hospital was in a position to move with a notice
of thirty-six hours. Little news came. Colonel Sichi went to
Lae, Saidor and Nadzeb to study functioning hospitals. He
reported to us that the Markau Valley, paralleling the northern
coast of New Guinea, was bristling with air installations. The
malaria and typhus rates were higher than in our section of the
island. We were anxious to move north and do our small part
in caring for the sick.


Good news came with the bad on the last two days of May.
We learned that when alerted we were scheduled to go with
the task force which took Hollandia. Something went wrong
with our orders, however, and the 37th Field Hospital was side-tracked.
This would have been an interesting experience. The
Surgeon of the Hollandia area was surprised that our unit did
not arrive. With this information came our assignment to the
Sixth Division which was already leaving the base. We would
leave within the next fortnight. Via the "Grapevine," we were

[p. <i>70</i>] | [<a href="psyc.get.jpg.aspx?display=page&amp;legacyid=1000048379-I00076&amp;api=new&amp;maxwidth=700">Page Image</a>]<br />

Jungle packs, jungle suits, new shoes, camouflaged helmet
liners, jungle boots were issued to us. We each received rations
for three days, new carbines, fifty pounds of ammunition and
five new thirty-inch machetes. We would probably land in this
area "west of Hollandia" on D day plus four, following the
medical regiment with its clearing and collecting companies.


This was the tense, expectant period we had long awaited.
We heard that the troops on Biak were encountering difficulties
and were calling for reserves. Unexpected resistance by tanks
and snipers was holding them up. We packed our bedding
rolls, foot lockers, musette bags and "val paks." We were allowed
two hundred pounds of personal equipment. Then we
sat on the edge of the ocean and oiled and reoiled our carbines,
waiting for embarkation. We were ready.


Deep in the jungles of New Guinea a new rumor intrigued
us. On 2 June 1944 we heard the "scuttlebutt": "News of the
invasion in Normandy — it will be on 5 June. Landing will
be at Le Havre and Cherbourg." I have since wondered how
this news trickled down to the Southwest Pacific! If we knew
about it at Milne Bay, the Germans must have known far
more only miles away from Great Britain. On June 7th this
"scuttlebutt" was confirmed.


General Eisenhower spent most of Monday night, June 7,
visiting paratroops in England as they boarded planes for
France. Berlin radio said that Hitler would take personal command
of Nazi defense forces. Six hundred and forty naval guns
hammered the invasion coast. The greatest mine-sweeping operation
in history was made.... British radio said Allies are
landing in Normandy.... Dieppe was taking heavy smashes.
... President Roosevelt, in a broadcast to the nation, lauded
the troops which had liberated Rome, "the cradle of Christianity."
Our losses were 20,000 killed in the Anzio drive, according
to Winston Churchill.


The above events were absolutely spine-tingling to all of us

[p. <i>71</i>] | [<a href="psyc.get.jpg.aspx?display=page&amp;legacyid=1000048379-I00077&amp;api=new&amp;maxwidth=700">Page Image</a>]<br />

Absolute confirmation of our Pacific "scuttlebutt" of June
2nd came from Supreme Headquarters in London on June
6th. One of the earliest broadcasts said that American, British
and Canadian troops landed on one of the heaviest fortified
sectors of France. Later broadcasts said the invasion coast extended
from Le Havre, at the mouth of the River Seine, to the
coast city of Cherbourg. Can you not envision our eager excitement
in the depths of New Guinea as we listened to the
faint broadcasts from our single, small short-wave Hallicrafters
radio?


At no time previously had the war scene looked so bright
for the Allied cause, Hitler's forces had once penetrated into
Russia in the north to Leningrad on the Baltic Sea. Their
deepest penetration south had been to Moscow and to Stalingrad
and they had almost arrived to the Caspian Sea at Vladikaukaz.
Now the Nazi attacks were being repulsed at Jassey in Rumania,
and the Hitler forces were driven back to Odessa on
the Black Sea in the south; the fighting before Kiev had ceased
and the liberated area extended north to Leningrad through
Vitebsk. The war was being won on the continent; Hitler's
"Drang Nach Osten" was being converted into a dismal, disastrous
Napoleonic fighting retreat with perhaps heavier casualties
than if we were on the offensive.

